= 6 Summary of Li et al. (2025)

The primary paper reviewed for this assignment is:

*Li, G., Shao, C., Zhang, Y., Li, J., Wang, P., & Ren, T. (2025). Multifunctional
self-emulsifying drug delivery system: an efficient strategy for oral delivery
of therapeutic peptides and proteins. Drug Delivery, 32(1), 2579137.*

This comprehensive review (published December 2025 in *Drug Delivery*, a Taylor
& Francis open-access journal) synthesizes the current state of knowledge on
SEDDS for oral peptide and protein delivery. The review covers:

- The four main barriers to oral biologic delivery (acidic pH, enzymes,
  thiol/disulfide exchange, mucus and epithelium).
- Three lipidization strategies for loading hydrophilic proteins into SEDDS:
  hydrophobic ion pairing (HIP), H-bond pairing, and prodrug design — with a
  detailed table of counterions and their peptide substrates.
- Protection mechanisms: SEDDS provides effective shielding against enzymatic
  degradation, thiol/disulfide exchange, and lipase-mediated hydrolysis.
- Absorption enhancement strategies: droplet size optimization, PEG coating,
  zeta potential-changing ("flip-flop") excipients, mucolytic agents,
  cell-penetrating peptide decoration, and zwitterionic surface engineering.
- Reverse micelle-containing SEDDS as an emerging high-payload platform.
- Compelling in vivo data: 10+ studies demonstrating 2–18 fold improvements in
  oral bioavailability for insulin, exenatide, octreotide, leuprolide, and
  calcitonin.
- Challenges: identifying optimal excipient combinations, understanding the
  in vivo fate of SEDDS components, and the need for advanced analytical
  tools and artificial intelligence to accelerate formulation development.

= 7 Conclusion

SEDDS represent a versatile and increasingly mature platform for addressing the
long-standing challenge of oral biologic delivery. As reviewed by Li et al.
(2025), all of the main barriers encountered in oral peptide and protein
delivery — acidic pH, enzymes, sulfhydryl barriers, mucus, and epithelium —
can be addressed with well-designed SEDDS. Hydrophobic ion pairing and other
lipidization methods enable high drug loading, while multifunctional auxiliary
agents (charge-changing compounds, zwitterions, mucolytic enzymes, cell-
penetrating peptides) confer both high mucus permeation and cellular uptake.
The in vivo data are compelling: SEDDS have achieved oral bioavailability
ranging from 2% to 28% (relative to SC injection) for peptides including
insulin, exenatide, and octreotide.

The broader SEDDS landscape — including S-SMEDDS, S-SEDDS, and PC-SEDDS —
offers additional opportunities for formulation optimization, though these
variants remain less explored for biologics compared to small molecules.
Future progress will depend on deeper understanding of excipient-nanocarrier
interactions, scalable manufacturing processes, and the integration of
computational tools for rational formulation design. With continued advances,
SEDDS are poised to play a transformative role in the oral delivery of
therapeutic peptides and proteins.

